				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Usually in my lessons I tell what you 'should' be doing to get your bass playing to the next level...</p>
<p>So, I thought it'd be fun for this lesson to switch that around and to tell you <span style="text-decoration: underline;">what NOT to do</span>.</p>
<p><strong>In this lesson I discuss:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Why knowing your <a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/play-multiple-octave-scales-like-bad-ass.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">scales and arpeggios</a> will NOT make you a better soloist</li>
<li>The simple things you could be doing to make you <a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/outlining-the-changes.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">a better soloist</a> - but you're probably not</li>
<li>What you <em>really</em> NEED to know about <a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/developing-your-vocabulary-with-the-blues-scale.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">the blues scale</a> (we've ALL been guilty of this)</li>
<li>And, much more</li>
</ul>
<p>I'm going to share the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">top 10 bass soloing MISTAKES</span> that SO many bass players are making... in fact, it's very likley that you're already making some of these mistakes - I know I've made them all!</p>
<p>As always, see you in the shed...</p>
<p>Scott :)</p>
